args: Sorry to trouble you for an examination.
Not at all. I'm a nurse! If anything,\nI should be the one to apologize...
Please, you've done more than enough.\nThe medicine you've given me feels like\nit's helping considerably.
Just the same, don't push yourself.\nThe medication is only a stopgap measure.\nIt can stabilize your mana for now, but...
Until we can learn the root cause of your\ncondition, I'm afraid there's no telling\nwhen you might lose consciousness again.
Nrgh, this sensation... I fear it's...\nBut even so, I've a duty to see done.
What happened to you? Don't tell me a\nfiend did this! Given your strength, I can't\nimagine...
That's my line. Why are you out here in the\nmiddle of nowhere? Actually, forget that.\nYou look like you're in pain. You all right?
Yes, I just...need a little while to rest.\n...Ngh!
You always pull this tough-guy\nact when you're falling apart!
I've got a little hideout nearby.\nLet's get you there so you can rest up.
Yes. I feel much better, thank you.
(This home looks exactly like the one from\nthe memories the armor showed to me.\nDoes that mean that woman used to...?)
Curious about this place, I take it?
It was a hideout my ancestor once used.\nIt's made for a convenient hub between\nall my travels.
Or...was there something specific about\nit on your mind?
...I see. So you came here to find the\ncause of your condition.
I didn't have any other leads to pursue.\nPlus, I was curious to see where this\narmor was made firsthand.
Huh. I didn't take you for such a free spirit.
I'm not simply sightseeing, you know.
I know. I was only teasing.\nBut back to your condition...
Wait there a second. When I was cleaning\nthis place up, I found a journal containing \nan interesting tidbit. I think it's...here?
Aha. Found it. Anyway, I flipped through it\nearlier, and there was a mention of that\narmor among my ancestor's notes.
I was curious, but I felt a little bad reading\nsomeone else's diary, so I didn't dig too\ndeep into it.
The passage was around... Here, yeah.\n＂The tremendous protection imbued in the\narmor brings with it tremendous strain.＂
＂Wearing it disrupts one's mana, meaning\nthat extended wear will cause even the\nideal user to eventually—＂
Burn their own life force and die,\nI assume?
That's horrible! But...back when you saved\nme, there was no sign of that at all!
I suppose that means I'm close to that\n＂ideal user.＂ At first, it must not have had\na noticeable effect on my internal mana.
But if you keep wearing it...
Thank you, Nino. That clarifies the cause\nof my malady. It was just as I suspected.
At least now you know never to use it\nagain. Even the best armor isn't much\nhelp if it kills you.
Wait. Don't tell me you plan to keep\nwearing it? Tobias, you could DIE!
I understand that. But I want to protect the\npeople's happiness however I can, even if\nit comes at the cost of my life.
Why push yourself to such extremes?
My father was a bishop of the Church.\nStern, but kind. He always put the needs\nof the faithful above his own.
He was the sort of man who would share\nhis last crumb of bread with his neighbor,\neven if he went starving.
He rarely smiled, but everyone who came\nto see him left with a smile. I loved him\ndearly, and respect him with all my heart.
I became a knight because I wanted to be\nlike him. To serve others.
That's still no reason to sacrifice your\nown life in the process.
But that's the ideal I've chased all my life.\nAnd it's the will imbued into this armor.
You're telling me that armor has a will?
I've inherited the resolve She put into it—\nthe will of the Goddess to see the people\nmade happy, even at the cost of Her life.
For that, I will fight until my body breaks!
Please don't stop me, Nino.\nThis is my duty to see done.
